On 7/30/07, Jon Hanna &lt;jon@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Steve Loughran wrote:
&gt; &gt; One strength of JSON is that its simplicity is like XMLRPC -the effort
&gt;
&gt; You mean the spec is inconsistent and buggy but because it fits on one
&gt; page it seems like it&#39;s simple on first pass?
&gt;
&gt; I hear a lot of the bugs in XMLRPC have been fixed, but really it&#39;s
&gt; &quot;simplicity&quot; is chimeric.
&gt;

yep. But it also means you dont need to commit to a SOAP stack vendor,
have a toolchain whose whole aim in life is to hide the incoming data,
or rely on reverse-generated WSDL and XSD to describe the operations.

This doesnt mean I&#39;m a fan of XMLRPC (I&#39;m not), only that I dont
consider much of SOAP, other than SOAPFault, to be an improvement.
SOAPFault I do like, but only as long as you stay in the XML space,
and stop trying to turn it back into a predefined native fault type,
which will drop on the floor all the interesting stuff the stack
added, like (in Axis), the hostname, a stack trace and any HTTP error
codes picked up on the way.

-steve
